<tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" numbered="false" root="false"><frontmatter><anchor>2140</anchor> <rss>jms-00NO.xml</rss> <taxon>Proposition</taxon> <addr>jms-00NO</addr><route>jms-00NO.xml</route>  <date><year>2024</year> <month>1</month> <day>31</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local" jonmsterling="addr">Jon Sterling</link></author> <contributor><link href="marcelofiore.xml" type="local" marcelofiore="addr">Marcelo Fiore</link></contributor></authors> <title>Characterisation of <link href="jms-00NL.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00NL" title="Well-founded relation">well-foundness</link> in terms of chains</title>   </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>A relation <tex>\prec \colon  A \mathbin { \nrightarrow }  A</tex> is <link href="jms-00NL.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00NL" title="Well-founded relation">well-founded</link> if and only if there are no infinite descending <span style="white-space: nowrap"><tex>\prec</tex>-chains</span> in <tex>A</tex>, i.e. no infinite sequences <tex>a_0,a_1, \ldots ,a_i, \ldots</tex> such that <tex>a_0 \succ  a_1 \succ \cdots  a_i \succ \cdots</tex>.</p></mainmatter> <backmatter><contributions/> <context><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" numbered="false" root="false"><frontmatter><anchor>2141</anchor> <rss>jms-00NK.xml</rss>  <addr>jms-00NK</addr><route>jms-00NK.xml</route>  <date><year>2024</year> <month>1</month> <day>31</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local" jonmsterling="addr">Jon Sterling</link></author> <contributor><link href="marcelofiore.xml" type="local" marcelofiore="addr">Marcelo Fiore</link></contributor></authors> <title>Well-foundedness and induction</title>   </frontmatter> <mainmatter><tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" toc="true" numbered="true" root="false"><frontmatter><anchor>2142</anchor> <rss>jms-00NL.xml</rss> <taxon>Definition</taxon> <addr>jms-00NL</addr><route>jms-00NL.xml</route>  <date><year>2024</year> <month>1</month> <day>31</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local" jonmsterling="addr">Jon Sterling</link></author> <contributor><link href="marcelofiore.xml" type="local" marcelofiore="addr">Marcelo Fiore</link></contributor></authors> <title>Well-founded <link href="jms-00I7.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00I7" title="Relation">relation</link></title>   </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>Let <tex>\prec   \colon  A \mathbin { \nrightarrow }  A</tex> be a <link href="jms-00I7.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00I7" title="Relation">relation</link> on a set <tex>A</tex>.</p><ol><li>An element <tex>m \in  S \subseteq  A</tex> is a <em><strong><span style="white-space: nowrap"><tex>\prec</tex>-minimal</span></strong></em> (henceforth, “minimal”) element of <tex>S</tex> when <tex>\lnot { \mathopen {} \left ( \exists  x \in  S \mathpunct {.}  x \prec  m \right ) \mathclose {}}</tex>.</li>
 <li>The binary <link href="jms-00I7.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00I7" title="Relation">relation</link> <tex>\prec</tex> on <tex>A</tex> is called <em><strong>well-founded</strong></em> whenever each non-empty subset of <tex>A</tex> has a minimal element.</li></ol></mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" toc="true" numbered="true" root="false"><frontmatter><anchor>2143</anchor> <rss>jms-00NM.xml</rss> <taxon>Example</taxon> <addr>jms-00NM</addr><route>jms-00NM.xml</route>  <date><year>2024</year> <month>1</month> <day>31</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local" jonmsterling="addr">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>A <link href="jms-00NK.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00NK" title="Well-foundedness and induction">well-founded relation</link> on the naturals</title>   </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>The “strictly less-than” <link href="jms-00I7.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00I7" title="Relation">relation</link> <tex>&lt; \colon \mathbb {N} \mathbin { \nrightarrow } \mathbb {N}</tex> is <link href="jms-00NL.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00NL" title="Well-founded relation">well-founded</link>.</p>
 
   
   <tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" toc="false" numbered="true" root="false"><frontmatter><anchor>2144</anchor>  <taxon>Proof</taxon>   <date><year>2024</year> <month>1</month> <day>31</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local" jonmsterling="addr">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors>    </frontmatter> <mainmatter>
 <p>Almost immediate: give a non-empty set of naturals, pick the smallest number.</p>
</mainmatter> </tree>
 
</mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" toc="true" numbered="true" root="false"><frontmatter><anchor>2145</anchor> <rss>jms-00NN.xml</rss> <taxon>Counterexample</taxon> <addr>jms-00NN</addr><route>jms-00NN.xml</route>  <date><year>2024</year> <month>1</month> <day>31</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local" jonmsterling="addr">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>A non-<link href="jms-00NL.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00NL" title="Well-founded relation">well-founded</link> relation on the integers</title>   </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>The strictly less-than <link href="jms-00I7.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00I7" title="Relation">relation</link> <tex>&lt; \colon \mathbb {Z} \mathbin { \nrightarrow } \mathbb {Z}</tex> is not <link href="jms-00NL.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00NL" title="Well-founded relation">well-founded</link>.</p>
 
   
   <tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" toc="false" numbered="true" root="false"><frontmatter><anchor>2146</anchor>  <taxon>Proof</taxon>   <date><year>2024</year> <month>1</month> <day>31</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local" jonmsterling="addr">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors>    </frontmatter> <mainmatter>
 <p>There is no smallest integer, so the set <tex>\mathbb {Z}</tex> has no <span style="white-space: nowrap"><tex>&lt;</tex>-minimal</span> element.</p>
</mainmatter> </tree>
 
</mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" toc="true" numbered="true" root="false"><frontmatter><anchor>2147</anchor> <rss>jms-00NO.xml</rss> <taxon>Proposition</taxon> <addr>jms-00NO</addr><route>jms-00NO.xml</route>  <date><year>2024</year> <month>1</month> <day>31</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local" jonmsterling="addr">Jon Sterling</link></author> <contributor><link href="marcelofiore.xml" type="local" marcelofiore="addr">Marcelo Fiore</link></contributor></authors> <title>Characterisation of <link href="jms-00NL.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00NL" title="Well-founded relation">well-foundness</link> in terms of chains</title>   </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>A relation <tex>\prec \colon  A \mathbin { \nrightarrow }  A</tex> is <link href="jms-00NL.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00NL" title="Well-founded relation">well-founded</link> if and only if there are no infinite descending <span style="white-space: nowrap"><tex>\prec</tex>-chains</span> in <tex>A</tex>, i.e. no infinite sequences <tex>a_0,a_1, \ldots ,a_i, \ldots</tex> such that <tex>a_0 \succ  a_1 \succ \cdots  a_i \succ \cdots</tex>.</p></mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" toc="true" numbered="true" root="false"><frontmatter><anchor>2148</anchor> <rss>jms-00NP.xml</rss> <taxon>Proposition</taxon> <addr>jms-00NP</addr><route>jms-00NP.xml</route>  <date><year>2024</year> <month>1</month> <day>31</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local" jonmsterling="addr">Jon Sterling</link></author> <contributor><link href="marcelofiore.xml" type="local" marcelofiore="addr">Marcelo Fiore</link></contributor></authors> <title>The principle of well-founded induction</title>   </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>Let <tex>\prec \colon  A \mathbin { \nrightarrow }  A</tex> be a <link href="jms-00NL.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00NL" title="Well-founded relation">well-founded relation</link> and fix a subset <tex>S \subseteq  A</tex>. Then <tex>A \subseteq  S</tex> holds if and only if for each <tex>x \in  A</tex> such that <tex>\forall  y \in  A \mathpunct {.}  y \prec  x \implies  y \in  S</tex>, we have <tex>x \in  S</tex>.</p><p>In other words, to show that every element of <tex>A</tex> lies in <tex>S</tex>, it is enough to show that for any element <tex>x \in  A</tex>, the elements below <tex>x</tex> lie in <tex>S</tex>.</p></mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" toc="true" numbered="true" root="false"><frontmatter><anchor>2149</anchor> <rss>jms-00NQ.xml</rss> <taxon>Corollary</taxon> <addr>jms-00NQ</addr><route>jms-00NQ.xml</route>  <date><year>2024</year> <month>1</month> <day>31</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local" jonmsterling="addr">Jon Sterling</link></author> <contributor><link href="marcelofiore.xml" type="local" marcelofiore="addr">Marcelo Fiore</link></contributor></authors> <title>Strong induction as <link href="jms-00NP.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00NP" title="The principle of well-founded induction">well-founded induction</link></title>   </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>The “strong” or “complete” induction principle for natural numbers states that for any subset <tex>S \subseteq   \mathbb {N}</tex>, we have <tex>\forall  x \in   \mathbb {N} \mathpunct {.}  x \in  S</tex> if and only if we have <tex>0 \in  S</tex> and, for any <tex>n \in   \mathbb {N}</tex> such that <tex>m \in  S</tex> for all <tex>m&lt;n</tex>, we have <tex>n \in  S</tex>. This is precisely the statement of <link href="jms-00NP.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00NP" title="The principle of well-founded induction">well-founded induction</link> for the <link href="jms-00NM.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00NM" title="A well-founded relation on the naturals">strictly less-than relation</link>.</p></mainmatter> </tree></mainmatter> </tree></context> <related><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" numbered="false" root="false"><frontmatter><anchor>2150</anchor> <rss>jms-00NL.xml</rss> <taxon>Definition</taxon> <addr>jms-00NL</addr><route>jms-00NL.xml</route>  <date><year>2024</year> <month>1</month> <day>31</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local" jonmsterling="addr">Jon Sterling</link></author> <contributor><link href="marcelofiore.xml" type="local" marcelofiore="addr">Marcelo Fiore</link></contributor></authors> <title>Well-founded <link href="jms-00I7.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00I7" title="Relation">relation</link></title>   </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>Let <tex>\prec   \colon  A \mathbin { \nrightarrow }  A</tex> be a <link href="jms-00I7.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00I7" title="Relation">relation</link> on a set <tex>A</tex>.</p><ol><li>An element <tex>m \in  S \subseteq  A</tex> is a <em><strong><span style="white-space: nowrap"><tex>\prec</tex>-minimal</span></strong></em> (henceforth, “minimal”) element of <tex>S</tex> when <tex>\lnot { \mathopen {} \left ( \exists  x \in  S \mathpunct {.}  x \prec  m \right ) \mathclose {}}</tex>.</li>
 <li>The binary <link href="jms-00I7.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00I7" title="Relation">relation</link> <tex>\prec</tex> on <tex>A</tex> is called <em><strong>well-founded</strong></em> whenever each non-empty subset of <tex>A</tex> has a minimal element.</li></ol></mainmatter> </tree></related> <backlinks/> <references/></backmatter></tree>